post_text:
[ üö© CBTech Announcement üö©]

CBtech is in the process of enrolling their students. To enroll, the process begins with your high school counselor.

Students enrolled at CBTECH are part of the Moses Lake School District and will start school remotely on September 9th. Teachers will be personally contacting every student between September 9-11. Instruction will begin on Monday, September 14.

Every student will be contacted prior to September 9 for the purpose of verifying cell phone numbers and email addresses. If you are not contacted, please call the CBTECH office at (509) 793-7000. Our teachers are currently learning new ways in which to engage students in online learning.

By Monday September 28, our plan is to begin bringing students on campus by cohorts. We hope to get all students on campus as soon as we can full time. We know that our ‚Äúhands on‚Äù programs need to be taught in the labs we have at CBTECH.

When we learn new information, we will be in communication with all students enrolled in CBTECH and their families.

[ Now accepting Preschool Enrollment ]

We offer preschool classes (in-person and remote) embracing developmentally appropriate practices that focus on the development of the whole child.

shared_text:
Dr. Joshua Meek
August 19 at 3:09 PM ¬∑

Mask Up MLSD!

We are not powerless in this crisis!

As we prepare for a back to school time for our community's youth like never before it may feel like things are beyond our control. But I wear a mask because it is something I can control -- to do my part to help the spread of this virus. Our kids need us as role models and to show them we can be strong, and we can get through this. If we think it is tough on us, imagine the impacts on young ones.

I invite everyone to join me in being proud to bring community awareness and this reminder. I never hoped that one day I would get to wear a mask, but this opportunity for impact is far greater than we may ever realize. Join me by updating your profile picture with the reasons why you Mask Up. We've got this!

#MaskUpMLSD

post_text:
[ UPDATE 7.14.20 ]

We recognize that many school districts have been announcing their plans for return and appreciate their ability to do so quickly.

However, we anticipate that health and safety guidelines will continue to change throughout the summer. We also expect more reopening guidelines from local authorities throughout the next coming weeks.

While many of you are anxious to see what school will look like this fall, we want you to know our Reopening Taskforce is placing greater value on developing a thorough, well-informed plan with the health, safety, and wellbeing of our community as our top priority.

Here is our tentative planning timeline:

June 9 ‚Äì July 30 // Develop our School Recovery Plan
July 24 // Submit our plan to Grant County Health District for review
July 30 // Submit our plan to the School Board for discussion and review
August 15 // Submit the final plan to the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI)
August 15 ‚Äì September 1 // Begin implementing/adjusting School Recovery
September 2 // First day of school!

[ UPDATE 6.9.20]

The results are in!

Thank you to our parents, students, staff, and community members that participated in our survey. We had over 1500 responses and read each and every one of your comments and concerns.

While we are early in our work, please know that we are doing everything within our power to have students and staff safe in the school environment -- as normal as possible. We continue to have a positive working relationship with the Grant County Health District and they are a member of our reopening team.

Many of you have questions regarding face coverings‚Äì At this time, DOH requires everyone in a school building or on a school bus to wear a face covering. Read more about our planning efforts and FAQs for Reopening WA Schools here:

‚ÑπÔ∏è www.mlsd161.org/reopening/

Plus, it‚Äôs not too late! Your feedback is important and will continue to inform our decisions as we develop plans for reopening this fall. Take our Feedback Survey here:

The results are in!

View Survey Results here --> https://bit.ly/MLSDresults

Thank you to our parents, students, staff, and community members that participated in our survey. We had over 1500 responses and read each and every one of your comments and concerns.

While we are early in our work, please know that we are doing everything within our power to have students and staff safe in the school environment -- as normal as possible. We continue to have a positive working relationship with the Grant County Health District and they are a member of our reopening team.

shared_text:
Dr. Joshua Meek
June 18 at 9:36 PM ¬∑

Today will be forever be one of my favorite days at work. Just after 9:00 am this morning we officially broke ground on Vicki I. Groff Elementary. Moses Lake's newest elementary school servicing the students on the east side of our community beginning in the Fall 2021. While the construction is exciting and the future for our young Gators is even better there is so much more to this story. To be there today and get to turn dirt and launch this project alongside Vicki Groff is an honor. Vicki selflessly served the Moses Lake community for over 30 years as a school board member. She was one of the first people I ever met from Moses Lake in 2004 when we arrived on this new adventure. She has been a key player in every step of my career, especially my role as Superintendent. Not every day of that path has been perfect, but I have always had a champion in Vicki on my side. Nobody deserves a school named after them as much as this wonderful lady. Thank you Vicki for all that you have done for me and many others . . . #GroffGators

Your children may be eligible for food assistance through a new program called P-EBT (an Emergency School Meals Program through OSPI). P-EBT provides eligible families with funds to make up for the cost of meals while school was closed.

DETAILS: k12.wa.us/PEBT

ELIGIBILITY:
‚Ä¢ Children in grades k-12 who receive free/reduced-price school meals
‚Ä¢ Immigration status does not matter for P-EBT
‚Ä¢ P-EBT is intended to replace meals missed while schools closed due to COVID-19.
‚Ä¢ Children are allowed to get free meals from other community sites and get P-EBT at the same time (they are separate programs).
‚Ä¢ Find out if you are eligible and how to apply by visiting www.mlsd161.org/apps/pages/free-reduced to download forms and applications.

[ ATTN: Chief Moses Middle School ]

To Chief Moses Middle School 8th Grade Students and Parents:

As you know, with our Covid-19 shutdown, we were unable to do our usual 8th Grade Promotion ceremony this year. We want each 8th grader and their parents to know how much we have appreciated the opportunity to be part of their education over the last three years. We have seen amazing growth in these young men and women during their time at Chief Moses. Please know that our best wishes go with all of you as you move on to Moses Lake High School. We will miss you!

We have a number of staff members who have been working on a slideshow tribute to 8th graders over the past couple of weeks.

‚è∞ At 1:00 PM on June 8th, an email containing a link to the slide show will go to all 8th grade students Please enjoy this slide show tribute with your student. All the best to the Class of 2024!

Stay healthy and stay safe!

Ms. Swisher, Principal
Mr. Sawyer, Assistant Principal
Mr. Nordsten, Assistant Principal

Our very own Park Orchard has won the Imagine Nation Beacon School Award for the 2019-20 school year. We are excited to be among the honored schools this year. Our students and teachers have worked consistently all year long in the #imaginelearning programs.

‚Ä¢ Imagine Nation Awards are part of the esteemed Imagine Learning motivational program igniting engagement and amplifying confidence for all learners.

‚Ä¢ The Beacon School Award was given to fewer than 100 schools (8 in the state of WA!) which exemplify the spirit of the Imagine Learning partnership, consistent program usage, and best practices in program implementation.

We are thrilled! #learning #education #motivation

Read more about the awards here: https://bit.ly/3b3LiRf

post_text:
Ms. Harless your students and families want you to know that you make a difference!

Ms. Harless, Teacher at Lakeview Elementary is being recognized as part of our Staff Appreciation Week for the amazing work she is doing.

One of her parents Samantha Doehne stated, ‚ÄúLast summer my family moved from the Portland Metro area. Our son was going into the 3rd grade and has always struggled in school due to his diagnosed ADHD. We prayed all summer long for his 3rd grade teacher and for his new school experience. When we met Ms. Harless we instantly loved her. She is deeply empathetic towards our son and we credit her for this being his most successful school year. She has brought tools to the table that have helped him but also is very patient and kind. Not only is he thriving academically but he now enjoys learning (reading specifically). We are so grateful for her!‚Äù

Congratulations Ms. Harless

#MLSDStaffWeSeeYou #NationalTeacherAppreciationWeek

Dr. Joshua Meek
May 6 at 5:59 PM ¬∑

There are many moments when I am proud of our team. I have to share this one from yesterday. Every year our FFA students at MLHS provide the plants to fill downtown Moses Lake. It may go unnoticed by some because it has become a staple of our city, but they really are a highlight downtown and for the awesome summer. This year that is obviously impacted. Yesterday a team of over 40 staff members from our district volunteered and did the work. Not only is this an amazing support of our awesome FFA students and advisors, but this is what community is all about!

post_text:
Mrs. Waites your students and families want you to know that you make a difference!

Mrs. Waites, a teacher at Knolls Vista Elementary, is being recognized as part of our Staff Appreciation Week for the amazing work she is doing.

Aracely Corral, mother of Jese, stated, "I never thought I would have to teach my own child. I know that sounds awful but we are so conditioned to leaving this huge responsibility of teaching our children to our teachers and schools and now that we have to help our own kids we are realizing the enormous job our teachers do. Mrs. Waites has listened to my frustrations and helped facilitate me helping my child with his work. Literally, my anxiety was through the roof and a phone call with her helped us figure things out and I felt so much calmer! She is calm, collected and my son gets so excited to Zoom with her and his class. It‚Äôs obvious she really cares about her students."

Congratulations Mrs. Waites!

#MLSDStaffWeSeeYou #NationalTeacherAppreciationWeek

GARDEN KITS in the MAKING!!!

We cannot begin to express our gratitude for the 100+ volunteers that have spent their Saturday morning filling over 10,000 bags with various vegetable seeds, fertilizer, and potatoes for community Garden Kits.

And a huge THANK YOU to our school board president, Elliott Goodrich, for spearheading the operation and our Local Farms for their donations to our community!

Crites Moscow: Peas, Beans, and Sweet Corn seed
Semenis: Peas, Beans, and other carrot seed
Syngenta: Sweet Corn seed
Brotherton: Peas, Beans
Harris-Moran: Sweet Corn
Sakata: Broccoli and carrots and other seed
Spokane Hutterian Brethren: potato seed
Washington Potato Commission: Potato seed and packaging
CHS-Sun Basin: 7500 lbs of fertilizer
Wilbur-Ellis: All bags and packaging
Moses Lake School District: staff/student/family volunteers
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints: volunteers

Garden Kits will be available to the community next week ‚Äì Details to follow!

[ 04.22.20 GRADING UPDATE ]

Yesterday, April 21st, OSPI announced statewide instruction to school districts regarding grading expectations during extended school closure.

While this announcement is as new to us as it is for our staff, students, parents, and community members, we are prepared to quickly align the new state amendments with our remote learning model.

*** We understand you have many questions and we hope to answer those questions in the following days, however, we must ask for your patience and understanding while we navigate these changes.***

Please note, there are several elements of local school district decisions that still need to be addressed before we can best respond to your concerns and define what our grading resolution looks like throughout the district.

Regardless of the new grading amendments, we will continue to provide our best remote instruction and will remain strongly committed to the success of all students!

Are you struggling with assisting your child with math during this remote instruction?

A common concern we are hearing involves parent's feelings of uncertainty in assisting their child with math. The math is not new, but today's mathematical instruction is heavily focused on mathematical thinking instead of remembering steps and formulas.

Our Remote Learning Hub is filled with great resources for assisting students and parents. I want to draw your attention to a new section where our Elementary Math Coach Mr. Kalmbach has put together some quick videos to assist with at home support and assistance. We can do this!

Check out the Learning Hub for this and other great resources at:

www.mlsd161.org

The response to the food box distribution this morning was far greater than anticipated. This is causing an unusually high volume of traffic and gridlock in the immediate area on Pioneer Way. We apologize to our neighbors and the area. While we didn‚Äôt anticipate this, it certainly shows the need that exists across our community. We believe the aid in serving that need outweighs the inconveniences created.

If you are in line for distribution please make sure you are:
- Not violating road laws and rules
- Do not block entrances and exits for local businesses
- Be kind and allow to conduct their business as needed
- Be respectful and patient of your surroundings
- Practice good decision making and common sense

shared_text:
Dr. Joshua Meek
April 14 at 12:37 AM ¬∑

Gracie Smith you are a ROCK STAR!

‚ÄúThe time is always right to do the right thing.‚Äù - Martin Luther King Jr.

Moses Lake High School freshman Gracie Smith has started making homemade hand sanitizer to benefit others. Gracie, and her mother Candy, started the project to make hand sanitizer for health care workers on the front lines. Since that time their project has exploded and they are now including fire fighters, EMTs, Columbia Basin Herald employees, community members, and others that are high risk. Their generosity and giving spirit is admirable and touching.

Gracie - way to be a leader among your peers in using your talents to benefit others, and especially in this time of need. It is mind boggling to think that our world has gotten to a place where things we used to take for granted have now become rare finds, like hand sanitizer. But your care for others is amazing. Way to go!

Students, staff, parents, and our entire community are doing amazing things during these times. May these stories of our ROCK STARS brighten your day.

#MLSDStrong #MLSDRockStar

shared_text:
Dr. Joshua Meek
April 7 at 3:13 AM ¬∑

Ryan Hays you are a ROCK STAR!

‚ÄúTough times don‚Äôt last; Tough people do!‚Äù

Frontier Middle School 8th grader Ryan Hays began doing chalk art on her driveway to beat the isolation of staying home and staying healthy. Soon her artwork was noticed and featured by the Columbia Basin Herald including photographs of her awesome work. Recently McDougall Insurance hired her to paint their office windows, the City of Moses Lake wants to use her artwork on the city‚Äôs Facebook page, and now McDougall Insurance will be donating funds to local charity in Ryan‚Äôs name.

Ryan I am impressed by your artwork, but more impressed by your spirit! What a thoughtful way of brightening the world for us all to enjoy!

Students, staff, parents, and our entire community are doing amazing things during these times. May these stories of our ROCK STARS brighten your day.
#MLSDStrong #MLSDRockStar

post_text:
[UPDATE 3.26.20]

We have been informed by the Grant County Health District that a Moses Lake High School staff member has tested positive for COVID-19 (Coronavirus).

The Moses Lake High School staff member‚Äôs last day of contact on our High School campus was on 3/16/20. The guidelines for quarantine are 14 days after exposure. All individuals believed to have been exposed or in contact with the staff member will receive communication directly from the Health District.

We know that this news is concerning. We urge you to please remain at home and monitor your family‚Äôs symptoms through Monday, March 31st.

Symptoms include fever, cough, and shortness of breath. If you or your child develop symptoms please contact your health care provider for guidance.

With an increasing number of COVID-19 cases, GCHD urges Grant County residents to take very seriously and adhere to the directive from Governor Inslee‚Äì limit social contact and shelter at home to minimize the spread of COVID-19 in the community.

For more information please visit the GCHD website at www.granthealth.org

post_text:
Tired of Netflix? Tune in to the School Board Meeting, Thursday, March 26 at 7pm, and stay up-to-date with the latest information in our District!

As we continue to honor 6 feet of social distancing, we will conduct Thursday's Board Meeting remotely and air it publically via LIVE STREAM.

Community members are encouraged to participate by viewing the Live Stream here: www.mlsd161.org/apps/pages/sb-livestream. In alignment with the Open Public Meetings Act and Governor Inslee's recent Proclamation 20-28, our revised meeting plan allows the opportunity and ability for all persons attending the meeting to hear each other at the same time.

We will also facilitate the public forum via written comment to: mlsddirectors@mlsd161.org

If for any reason computer or smart phone technology is not available we have made the meeting available for audio observation via phone by calling: (408) 638 0968 and using Meeting ID# 421 626 062

post_text:
School is happening as planned for Monday March 16, 2020

Governor Inslee's recent announcement for closure of restaurants, entertainment facilities, and groups over 50 is generating a few questions about school tomorrow. The Governor's order will not be signed until tomorrow, and his office has clarified that schools can meet tomorrow as planned. The school closure does not begin until Tuesday March 17.

As a district we take decisions like this very seriously and weigh out all of the options carefully.

Parents who feel like it is in their child's best interest to not attend are welcome to make that personal choice and be supported by the school district. We will release a set of make up times for distribution of a Chromebook for students not in attendance tomorrow.

post_text:
We encourage all students to attend school Monday, March 16th.

Grades 5-12:

‚Ä¢ Please bring your Chromebooks and chargers to all classes on Monday, March 16th to so that we can ensure they are functioning properly.

‚Ä¢ Teachers will be using Google Classroom to provide instruction during the school closure period and provide further instruction.

Grades K-4:

‚Ä¢ Students without Chromebooks will be receiving them.

‚Ä¢ Students will receive further instruction and guidance on upcoming remote instruction.

We are aware that not everyone has internet capabilities in their homes. We are working diligently to ensure all students will have access, more details and information will be provided soon.

‚ÄúMy parents came from Nigeria. They won a visa to come to America, it was a lottery for a visa. America is where they had their kids and raised a family. So I have been here all my life. I joined FFA when I was in a class where there was an assignment to memorize the Creed. I memorized the whole thing for extra credit. My teacher said there was an FFA Creed competition and that I should enter. So that is how I joined FFA. There is a lot to learn in FFA and I really like it. I now enter in public speaking contests and other contests that have to do with knowledge.
I know these skills will help me in the future. We did live on a small farm in the past, but I don‚Äôt live on a farm now. You don‚Äôt have to live on a farm to join FFA there is so much more to learn. I would like to go to UCLA and hopefully study graphic design. I am only a sophomore so I have time to decide all that.‚Äù

#agriculture #FFA #Patreon

Behind the scenes with agri.CULTURE ...
@patreon.com/agriculturepeople

Congratulations to Moses Lake High School Cheer Coaching staff for being selected as the WIAA Sportsmanship Winner as part of the WIAA State Championships. Several years ago, when I was the Principal at MLHS, Coach Mikey Carlile told me that she was going to create a "Cheer Dynasty." I am proud to work along side you and watch you do your work. It is clear that people across the state recognize your leadership and sportsmanship!

post_text:
You do NOT want to miss tonight's MLHS Unified Basketball game vs. Eastmont at 6:00 pm!

What are Unified Sports?

Dedicated to promoting social inclusion through shared sports training and competition experiences, Unified Sports joins people with and without intellectual disabilities on the same team. It was inspired by a simple principle: training together and playing together is a quick path to friendship and understanding.

In Unified Sports, teams are made up of people of similar age and ability, which makes practices more fun and games more challenging and exciting for all. Having sport in common is just one more way that preconceptions and false ideas are swept away.

Hope to see you there to cheer on our Chiefs!

Dr. Joshua Meek

It has been reported that last night as part of the Moses Lake High School and Davis High School Basketball Game a series of conflicts and inappropriate racial comments occurred. Like all schools in our league we highly value sportsmanship and mutual respect. Our district leadership team is taking these claims seriously and I can assure you that we are investigating the full scope of what transpired. While we have video surveillance that can be utilized, I would appreciate any first-hand knowledge and reports from those in attendance at the game. Please contact me directly through this account or email at jmeek@mlsd161.org. We must promote mutual understanding and respect for diversity and each other.

With the increase in workforce opportunities in the Columbia Basin Region, we are working toward providing programs for graduation that are equally preparing students who are looking to attend college or who are interested in studying a trade or entering the workforce right after high school.

‚ÄúAccording to Washington Roundtable, 70% of the state‚Äôs graduating class of 2030 will need to attain some postsecondary credential, degree or certificate to meet workforce needs.‚Äù ‚Äì Seattle Times editorial board

With MLHS, CBTECH and Real World Academy students will have access to the resources that will prepare them for long-term success after high school.

This editorial from the Seattle Times provides more information on the future Washington state workforce demands and new education requirements that Washington state public schools will be implementing.

post_text:
Mr. Chad Utter, Dean of Student and Instructor at CB Tech, speaks about how project based learning emulates a real world working environment.

Mr. Utter explains that these programs give students work-like experiences by teaching them how to adapt in real world situations and navigate through them. Real World Academy will offer programs that emphasize these principals and give students opportunities to work through situations similar to what they will find when they enter the workforce.

Learn more at https://realworldacademy2022.com
